<p>For a deeper breakdown, see our guide to <a href="/blog/keyword-research-for-blog-posts/">keyword research for blog posts</a>.</p>
<h3>Evaluate Keyword Difficulty</h3>
<p>Not all keywords are worth targeting. A new website will not rank for "best CRM software" against HubSpot and Salesforce. You need keywords where you can actually compete.</p>
<p>Look for keywords with these traits:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Monthly search volume above 100.</strong> Enough traffic to matter.</li>
<li><strong>Low to medium difficulty.</strong> If every result on page 1 has a Domain Authority above 60, skip it.</li>
<li><strong>Clear search intent.</strong> You can tell what the searcher wants.</li>
<li><strong>Business relevance.</strong> The searcher could become a customer.</li>
</ul>
<p>Long-tail keywords like "best CRM for real estate agents under $50" have less competition and higher conversion rates. Our <a href="/blog/keyword-optimization-guide/">keyword optimization guide</a> covers this in detail.</p>
<h3>Map Keywords to Pages</h3>
<p>Every page on your website should target 1 primary keyword and 2 to 3 related keywords. Never target the same keyword with 2 different pages. That creates keyword cannibalization.</p>
